'''Petter Furuseth''' (born 14 August 1978) is a Norwegian former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]] in the top-flight in Norway, Sweden and Denmark. He is formerly knowns as '''Petter Furuseth Olsen'''. Furuseth represented Norway at youth international level

Furuseth started his career in the local club [[Eik-T<U+00F8>nsberg]], before he played for [[SK Brann|Brann]], [[<U+00D6>rebro SK|<U+00D6>rebro]], [[Hammarby IF|Hammarby]], [[Stab<U+00E6>k Fotball|Stab<U+00E6>k]], [[Viborg FF|Viborg]] and [[FC Midtjylland]]. Furuseth announced his retirement from football in August 2008, but made a comeback five months later in [[FK Lyn|Lyn]]. He later had spell with Swedish clubs [[Assyriska F<U+00F6>reningen|Assyriska]] and Hammarby, before he returned to Norway where he has been playing and coaching at amateur level.

==Career==
Furuseth was born in [[T<U+00F8>nsberg]],<ref name="altomfotball" /> and played for the local team [[IL Flint]] during his youth.<ref name="NRKmoss">{{cite news |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/distrikt/ostfold/1.8000721 |language=Norwegian |title=Ny spiller klar for Moss |publisher=NRK |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> He played four matches for the Norwegian under-15 team in 1994, and one match for the under-16 the next year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fotball.no/Community/Profil/?fiksId=1911731 |language=Norwegian |title=Petter Furuseth's profil |work=fotball.no |publisher=Football Association of Norway |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>

Furuseth transferred to the [[Norwegian First Division]] side [[Eik-T<U+00F8>nsberg]] in 1996.<ref name="NRKmoss" /> He played his first matches for Eik in [[1997 Norwegian First Division|1997]], and played a total of 68 league-games for the club.<ref name="playerhistory">[http://www.playerhistory.com/player/3715 Petter Furuseth] on [[Playerhistory.com]] {{dead link|date=February 2013}}</ref> After Eik was relegated in [[2000 Norwegian First Division|2000]], Furuseth transferred to [[SK Brann]]. He made his debut in [[Tippeligaen]] against [[Moss FK|Moss]] on 16 April 2001,<ref name="altomfotball">{{cite web |url=http://www.altomfotball.no/element.do?cmd=player&personId=1786&tournamentId=1&seasonId=329&teamId=312&useFullUrl=false |language=Norwegian |title=Petter Furuseth |work= altomfotball.no |publisher=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |date= |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> and scored a total of 10 goals in 26 games in his first season at Brann.<ref name="playerhistory"/>

Furuseth stayed in Brann for three seasons, before he moved to [[Sweden]] and [[<U+00D6>rebro SK]]. During the first half of the 2004 season, Olsen was a great attraction in the [[Allsvenskan]], and it did not take long until he caught the eye of [[Hammarby IF|Hammarby]]. In September 2004, a <U+00D6>rebro in heavy debts was forced to sell him to league rivals Hammarby IF. In [[Stockholm]], Furuseth Olsen was transformed from striker to right winger,{{citation needed|date=March 2012}} and was awarded "Player of the year 2006" by the Hammarby-fans.<ref name="tv2moss">{{cite web |url=http://www.tv2.no/sport/fotball/adeccoligaen/petter-furuseth-klar-for-norsk-klubb-3711248.html |language=Norwegian |title=Petter Furuseth klar for norsk klubb |work=tv2.no |publisher=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> In October 2006, Furuseth Olsen made it clear that he were to leave Hammarby and Sweden, to return home to Norway, the reason being that he wanted to gain a spot on the [[Norwegian national football team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fotballmagasinet.no/index.php?mode=news&id=4758 |language=Norwegian |title=Utelukker ikke Norge-retur |work=fotballmagasinet.no |date=October 2006 |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref>

He transferred to [[Stab<U+00E6>k Fotball]] ahead of the 2007-season, but because of a conflict with [[Daniel Nannskog]] and the other players,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/sport/2007/06/25/504435.html |language=Norwegian |title=- Respekterte ikke nei til fyll |publisher=[[Dagbladet]] |date=25 June 2007 |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> he only played 4 matches for Stab<U+00E6>k and signed for the [[Denmark|Danish]] [[Viborg FF|Viborg]] in June 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/sport/2007/06/21/504136.html |language=Norwegian |title=Furuseth Olsen skrev under for Viborg |work= [[Norwegian News Agency]] |publisher=[[Dagbladet]] |date=21 June 2007 |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> The following winter, Furuseth transferred to [[FC Midtjylland]], but after three rounds of the [[2008<U+2013>09 Danish Superliga|2008<U+2013>09-season]] he asked to be released the contract and decided to retire.<ref name="aftenposten">{{cite web |url=http://fotball.aftenposten.no/eliteserien/article126372.ece |language=Norwegian |title=Petter Furuseth til Lyn |work= |publisher=[[Aftenposten]] |date=15 January 2009 |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/sport/2008/08/22/544416.html |language=Norwegian |title=Petter Furuseth Olsen legger opp |publisher=[[Dagbladet]] |date=22 August 2008 |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref>

Furuseth decided to make comeback in January 2009, and signed a two-year contract with [[FK Lyn|Lyn]]. He was transferred from FC Midtjylland, still formally his employer, for an undisclosed fee.<ref name="aftenposten"/> Furuseth played only two matches for Lyn in Tippeligaen during the first half of the season, and he was loaned out to [[Assyriska F<U+00F6>reningen|Assyriska]] so that Lyn, a club with mayor economic difficulties, could save some wage-expenses.<ref name="lynfotball">{{cite web |url=http://www.lynfotball.net/Lyn_Spiller.asp?id=333 |language=Norwegian |title=Petter Furuseth |work=lynfotball.net |publisher=[[FK Lyn]] |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vg.no/sport/fotball/norsk/artikkel.php?artid=557554 |language=Norwegian |title=Furuseth leies ut til Assyriska |work=vg.no |publisher=[[Verdens Gang]] |date=30 June 2009 |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> On 10 March 2010, his contract with Lyn was terminated by mutual consent,<ref name="lynfotball"/> and Furuseth moved back to [[Hammarby IF|Hammarby]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tv2.no/sport/fotball/petter-furuseth-tilbake-i-hammarby-3157335.html |language=Norwegian |title=Petter Furuseth tilbake i Hammarby |work=tv2.no |publisher=[[TV 2 (Norway)|TV 2]] |date=11 March 2010 |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref>

Furuseth moved back to Norway once more, and was signed by [[Moss FK|Moss]] as a playing assistant coach in February 2012, where he was working under the command of [[Tor Thodesen]], the coach who signed Furuseth from Eik-T<U+00F8>nsberg to Brann in 2000.<ref name="tv2moss"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moss-avis.no/sport/petter-furuseth-blir-assistent-i-mfk-1.6779411 |language=Norwegian |title=Petter Furuseth blir assistent i MFK |work=moss-avis.no |publisher=[[Moss Avis]] |date=17 February 2012 |accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> Furuseth left Moss in August 2012, blaiming personal reasons, and joined his old club Eik in the [[Norwegian Third Division|Third Division]] two weeks later,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tb.no/sport/petter-furuseth-tilbake-i-eik-1.7482577 |language=Norwegian |title=Petter Furuseth tilbake i Eik |publisher=T<U+00F8>nsbergs Blad |first=Sven-Erik |last=Syrstad |date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> where he was a part of the coaching staff. Ahead of the 2013 season, Furuseth joined [[Hus<U+00F8>y & Foynland IF]] as a [[player-coach]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hfif.no/fotball/index.php?side=41&nyhetid=3052&lagid=1 |language=Norwegian |title=Ny A-lags trener p<U+00E5> plass |publisher=Hus<U+00F8>y & Foynland IF |first=Geir |last=Levorsen |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>

